A dictionary in Python is an unordered, mutable collection of key–value pairs.
Each value is accessed using its unique key instead of an index.

Syntax
my_dict = { key : value }

Example

student = {
    "name": "Vijay",
    "age": 21,
    "marks": 85
}

print(student["name"])   # Output: Vijay

Important Features

Uses key–value pairs

Keys must be unique

Dictionary is mutable (can change values)

Keys can be strings, numbers, or tuples

Values can be of any data type